[normal]Written evidence from the Department for Transport (SLC 006)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1  [bold]Are[bold] current safety measures at level crossings adequat[bold]e? How should they be improved?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.  
[normal]The UK has one of the best level cross
[normal]ing safety records in Europe
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]Excluding suicides and suspected suicides, there were nine fatalities during 2012/13 (four pedestrians and five road vehicle occupants).  Although this is a slight rise from 2011/12, which saw the lowest number of fatalities 
[normal](5) and harm
[normal] in the last 10 years, it is still well below the 10-year average and perpetuates an overall 
[normal]trend towards 
[normal]improvement in safety performance.  
[normal]      
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.  
[normal]R
[normal]ail 
[normal]industry opera
[normal]tional errors or other process
[normal] 
[normal]issues 
[normal]only account for a small percen
[normal]tage of level crossing incidents.
[normal]  
[normal]Unfortunately, misuse 
[normal]remains 
[normal]a serious issue. 
[normal] 
[normal]The vast majority of incidents at level crossings arise from the behaviou
[normal]r of road users and pedestrians
[normal], either accidental or deliberate,
[normal] and 
[normal]it is 
[normal]these groups 
[normal]which 
[normal]carry
[normal] the highest risks as a result of their actions
[normal].  As well as the potential risks to
[normal] themselves
[normal], misuse by road users and pedestrians
[normal] also transfer
[normal]s
[normal] risks to train passengers as well as substantial costs from damage and delays to the rail industry.
[normal]  
[normal]The bes
[normal]t way to reduce risk at level crossings 
[normal]is
[normal] to ensure 
[normal]they 
[normal]are used safely and that 
[normal]any 
[normal]inst
[normal]ructions
[normal] 
[normal]displayed 
[normal]are 
[normal]followed
[normal].  
[normal]Network Rail has an on-going programme of public campaigns (see below
[normal])
[normal] aimed at raising awareness of the risks of level crossing misuse. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.  
[normal]The Rail Accident Investigation Branch has investigated 
[normal]41 
[normal]level crossing accidents and incidents
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]including 
[normal]publication of 
[normal]a specific report on the use of automated open level crossi
[normal]ngs
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]to ascertain if safety improvements are necessary
[normal].  
[normal]The majority 
[normal]of recommendations have resulted 
[normal]in 
[normal]imp
[normal]lementation by industry
[normal] and progress is monitored by the O
[normal]ffice of 
[normal]R
[normal]ail 
[normal]R
[normal]eg
[normal]ulation
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]While it is unfortunate that 
[normal]such investigations 
[normal]are sometimes necessary they are 
[normal]nevertheless 
[normal]a positive illustration of the industry safety framework and “lessons learned” systems in action.
[normal]  The Rail Accident Investigation Branch will be submitting its own more detailed submission to the Committee.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.  
[normal]The Department notes that it now receives significantly more representations on convenience issues, particularly those for road users and communities in which busy crossings are situated, than on safety
[normal] matters
[normal].
[normal]    
