[normal]3  [bold]How[bold] should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in relation to other demands on the rail [bold]budget?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]7.  
[normal]The Department considers that the most effective way to 
[normal]improve
[normal] 
[normal]safety at level crossings is to 
[normal]ensure that 
[normal]ring-fenced 
[normal]funding
[normal] is
[normal] made available to Network Rail
[normal] for this purpose and 
[normal]to 
[normal]direct resources at those level crossings with the highes
[normal]t risk factors
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.  
[normal]In
[normal] 
[normal]our July 2012 rail investment strategy, which 
[normal]set the 
[normal]strategic objectives for 
[normal]rail for
[normal] 2014 - 19), the Secretary of State 
[normal]included explicit notice of 
[normal]his wish 
[normal]for the industry to “
[normal]…reduce the risk of accidents at level crossings…
[normal]” and 
[normal]“
[normal]…
[normal]to make ring-fenced funding for this purpose
[normal]”
[normal].     
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.  
[normal]The Office of Rail Regulation
[normal], 
[normal]in its 
[normal]Draft Determination
[normal], 
[normal]has made provision for a 
[normal]£67
[normal] million
[normal] 
[normal]fund to enable Network Rail
[normal] to deliver a plan to maximise the reduction in risks of accidents at level crossings over and above meeting its existing legal obligations in this respect.  
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]O
[normal]ffice of 
[normal]R
[normal]ail 
[normal]R
[normal]egulation
[normal] will publ
[normal]ish its
[normal] final Determination on 31 October 2013.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.  
[normal]The
[normal] Department understands that a 
[normal]level crossing fund 
[normal]comprising an additional £10 million 
[normal]will 
[normal]also 
[normal]be made available by 
[normal]Scottish Ministers 
[normal]to support Network Rail, local a
[normal]uthorities and other local stakeholders in facilitating the closure of level crossings in Scotland.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.  
[normal]With funding from the Department, and as part of 
[normal]the RSSB
[normal] (formerly the Rail Safety &amp; Standards Board) rail industry research programme, Network Rail 
[normal]has also participated in a project to extend existing industry risk management models to level crossings.  The resulting All Level Crossings Risk Model (“ALCRM”) has further improved Network Rail’s ability to manage the risk to level crossing users, passen
[normal]gers and rail staff by targeting those crossings with the highest risk for remedial measures.  The ALCRM
[normal], in conjunction with further risk recognition and assessment work,
[normal] will be 
[normal]an important element
[normal] in identifying those
[normal] level crossings where funding will
[normal] provide the most substantial safety improvements
[normal] 
[normal]over 2014-19
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4  [bold]Is[bold] Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level crossings?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]12.  
[normal]Network Rail
[normal] has
[normal] 
[normal]a policy
[normal] to avoid new level crossings being built due to the associated safety and convenience issues
[normal] and to close existing level crossings 
[normal]so far as is reasonably practicable.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13.  
[normal]However, it would not be proportionate, or practical, to remove all existing cr
[normal]ossings
[normal] and 
[normal]Network Rail has 
[normal]put in place a significant program
[normal]me
[normal] of 19 projects designed to enhance level crossing risk management 
[normal]and reduce level crossing risk.  
[normal]Network Rail has also set itself challenging 
[normal]targets for
[normal] reducing level crossing risk by 25
[normal]% by the end of 
[normal]March 2014 
[normal]and a further 50% by 
[normal]March 2019
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1
[normal]4
[normal].  
[normal]The Department believes that these 
[normal]targets and initiatives, together with the 
[normal]ring-fenced funding Network Rail is likely to receive fo
[normal]r 2014-19
[normal], mean that
[normal] 
[normal]it will be able to give 
[normal]sufficient priority 
[normal]to impr
[normal]oving safety at level crossings.  
